<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="279" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="10.[824,1477,748,900]" pageId="10" pageNumber="279">
<emphasis box="[862,1447,748,772]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="279">
Distribution and ecology. – 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Buerki, Callm., Munzinger &amp; Lowry" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Buerki, Callm., Munzinger &amp; Lowry" baseAuthorityYear="2020" box="[1174,1447,748,772]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Lepidocupania" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="10" pageNumber="279" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="squamosa">Lepidocupania squamosa</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
is endemic to Grande Terre, where it grows in dense maquis-like scrub vegetation on serpentine, from 
<quantity box="[1223,1370,812,836]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="279" unit="m" value="400.0" valueMax="600.0" valueMin="200.0">200 to 600 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="ADEMA, F." pageId="10" pageNumber="279" refId="ref11451" refString="ADEMA, F. (1991). Cupaniopsis Radlk. (Sapindaceae): a monograph. Leiden Bot. Ser. 15." type="book" year="1991">ADEMA, 1991</bibRefCitation>
, and recent collections) and on isolated ultramafic mountains of the northeast (Boulinda, Kopéto, Tiébaghi, and Poum).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="279" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[824,1474,940,1156]" pageId="10" pageNumber="279">
<emphasis box="[862,1210,940,964]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="279">
Notes. – 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Buerki, Callm., Munzinger &amp; Lowry" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Buerki, Callm., Munzinger &amp; Lowry" baseAuthorityYear="2020" box="[953,1210,940,964]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Lepidocupania" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="10" pageNumber="279" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="squamosa">Lepidocupania squamosa</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
was assigned an IUCN risk of extinction status of “Endangered” by 
<bibRefCitation author="JAFFRE, T." pageId="10" pageNumber="279" pagination="109 - 135" refId="ref12116" refString="JAFFRE, T., P. BOUCHET &amp; J. M. VEILLON (1998). Threatened plants of New Caledonia: is the system of protected areas adequate? Biodivers. Conserv. 7: 109 - 135." type="journal article" year="1998">JAFFRÉ et al. (1998)</bibRefCitation>
. Since this assessment was conducted, a large portion of the vegetation on the Tiébaghi massif has been cleared for mining, which has surely led to further population decline (especially concerning since this area contained the largest subpopulation of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Buerki, Callm., Munzinger &amp; Lowry" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Buerki, Callm., Munzinger &amp; Lowry" baseAuthorityYear="2020" box="[1011,1136,1133,1156]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Lepidocupania" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="10" pageNumber="279" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="squamosa">
<emphasis box="[1011,1136,1133,1156]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="279">L. squamosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
